Differentially Private Low-dimensional Synthetic Data from High-dimensional Datasets

Yiyun He Department of Mathematics, University of California Irvine yiyunh4@uci.edu ,Â  Thomas Strohmer Department of Mathematics and Center of Data Science and Artificial Intelligence Research, University of California Davis strohmer@math.ucdavis.edu ,Â  Roman Vershynin Department of Mathematics, University of California Irvine rvershyn@uci.edu Â andÂ  Yizhe Zhu Department of Mathematics, University of California Irvine yizhe.zhu@uci.edu
Abstract.

Differentially private synthetic data provide a powerful mechanism to enable data analysis while protecting sensitive information about individuals. However, when the data lie in a high-dimensional space, the accuracy of the synthetic data suffers from the curse of dimensionality. In this paper, we propose a differentially private algorithm to generate low-dimensional synthetic data efficiently from a high-dimensional dataset with a utility guarantee with respect to the Wasserstein distance. A key step of our algorithm is a private principal component analysis (PCA) procedure with a near-optimal accuracy bound that circumvents the curse of dimensionality. Unlike the standard perturbation analysis, our analysis of private PCA works without assuming the spectral gap for the covariance matrix.

1. Introduction

As data sharing is increasingly locking horns with data privacy concerns, privacy-preserving data analysis is becoming a challenging task with far-reaching impact. Differential privacy (DP) has emerged as the gold standard for implementing privacy in various applications [24]. For instance, DP has been adopted by several technology companiesÂ [21] and has also been used in connection with the release of Census 2020 dataÂ [2]. The motivation behind the concept of differential privacy is the desire to protect an individualâ€™s data while publishing aggregate information about the database, as formalized in the following definition:

where the probability is with respect to the randomness of â„³â„³{\mathcal{M}}.

However, utility guarantees for DP are usually provided only for a fixed, predefined set of queries. Hence, it has been frequently recommended that differential privacy may be combined with synthetic data to achieve more flexibility in private data sharingÂ [28, 7]. Synthetic datasets are generated from existing datasets and maintain the statistical properties of the original dataset. Hence, the datasets can be shared freely among investigators in academia or industry, without security and privacy concerns.

Yet, computationally efficient construction of accurate differentially private synthetic data is challenging. Most research on private synthetic data has been concerned with counting queries, range queries, or kğ‘˜k-dimensional marginals, see, e.g.,Â [28, 51, 9, 52, 23, 50, 12]. Notable exceptions areÂ [55, 11, 19]. Specifically,Â [11] provides utility guarantees with respect to the 1-Wasserstein distance. Invoking the Kantorovich-Rubinstein duality theorem, the 1-Wasserstein distance accuracy bound ensures that all Lipschitz statistics are preserved uniformly. Given that numerous machine learning algorithms are Lipschitz [54, 39, 13, 46], this provides data analysts with a vastly increased toolbox of machine learning methods for which one can expect similar outcomes for the original and synthetic data.

For instance, for the special case of datasets living on the dğ‘‘d-dimensional Boolean hypercube [0,1]dsuperscript01ğ‘‘[0,1]^{d} equipped with the Hamming distance, the results inÂ [11] show that there exists an Îµğœ€\varepsilon-DP algorithm with an expected utility loss that scales like

(log(Îµn)32/(Îµn))1/d,\left(\log(\varepsilon n)^{\frac{3}{2}}/(\varepsilon n)\right)^{1/d}, (1.1)

where nğ‘›n is the size of the dataset. WhileÂ [31] succeeded in removing the logarithmic factor inÂ (1.1), it can be shown that the rate inÂ (1.1) is otherwise tight. Consequently, the utility guarantees inÂ [11, 31] are only useful when dğ‘‘d, the dimension of the data, is small (or if nğ‘›n is exponentially larger than dğ‘‘d). In other words, we are facing the curse of dimensionality. The curse of dimensionality extends beyond challenges associated with Wasserstein distance utility guarantees. Even with a weaker accuracy requirement, the hardness result from Uhlman and Vadhan [51] shows that n=polyâ€‹(d)ğ‘›polyğ‘‘n=\mathrm{poly}(d) is necessary for generating DP-synthetic data in polynomial time while maintaining approximate covariance.

InÂ [19], the authors succeeded in constructing DP synthetic data with utility bounds where dğ‘‘d in (1.1) is replaced by (dâ€²+1)superscriptğ‘‘â€²1(d^{\prime}+1), assuming that the dataset lies in a certain dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional subspace. However, the optimization step in their algorithm exhibits exponential time complexity in dğ‘‘d, see [19, Section 4.1].

This paper presents a computationally efficient algorithm that does not rely on any assumptions about the true data. We demonstrate that our approach enhances the utility bound from dğ‘‘d to dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime} in (1.1) when the dataset is in a dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional affine subspace. Specifically, we derive a DP algorithm to generate low-dimensional synthetic data from a high-dimensional dataset with a utility guarantee with respect to the 1-Wasserstein distance that captures the intrinsic dimension of the data.

Our approach revolves around a private principal component analysis (PCA) procedure with a near-optimal accuracy bound that circumvents the curse of dimensionality. Different from classical perturbation analysis [15, 25] that utilizes the Davis-Kahan theorem [17] in the literature, our accuracy analysis of private PCA works without assuming the spectral gap for the covariance matrix.

1.2. Comparison to previous results

Private synthetic data

Most existing work considered generating DP-synthetic datasets while minimizing the utility loss for specific queries, including counting queries [9, 28, 22], kğ‘˜k-way marginal queries [51, 23], histogram release [1]. For a finite collection of predefined linear queries Qğ‘„Q, [28] provided an algorithm with running time linear in |Q|ğ‘„|Q| and utility loss grows logarithmically in |Q|ğ‘„|Q|. The sample complexity can be reduced if the queries are sparse [23, 9, 19]. Beyond finite collections of queries, [55] considered utility bound for differentiable queries, and recent works [11, 31] studied Lipschitz queries with utility bound in Wasserstein distance. [19] considered sparse Lipschitz queries with an improved accuracy rate. [6, 27, 40, 56] measure the utility of DP synthetic data by the maximum mean discrepancy (MMD) between empirical distributions of the original and synthetic datasets. This metric is different from our chosen utility bound in Wasserstein distance. Crucially, MMD does not provide any guarantees for Lipschitz downstream tasks.

Our work provides an improved accuracy rate for low-dimensional synthetic data generation. Compared to [19], our algorithm is computationally efficient and has a better accuracy rate. Besides [19], we are unaware of any work on low-dimensional synthetic data generation from high-dimensional datasets. While methods from [11, 31] can be directly applied if the low-dimensional subspace is known, the subspace would be non-private and could reveal sensitive information about the original data. The crux of our paper is that we do not assume the low-dimensional subspace is known, and our DP synthetic data algorithm protects its privacy.

Private PCA

Private PCA is a commonly used technique for differentially private dimension reduction of the original dataset. This is achieved by introducing noise to the covariance matrix [45, 15, 32, 25, 35, 36, 58]. Instead of independent noise, the method of exponential mechanism is also extensively explored [38, 15, 35]. Another approach, known as streaming PCA [47, 34], can also be performed privately [29, 42].

The private PCA typically yields a private dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional subspace ğ•^dâ€²subscript^ğ•superscriptğ‘‘â€²\widehat{\mathbf{V}}_{d^{\prime}} that approximates the top dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional subspace ğ•dâ€²subscriptğ•superscriptğ‘‘â€²\mathbf{V}_{d^{\prime}} produced by the standard PCA. The accuracy of private PCA is usually measured by the distance between ğ•^dâ€²subscript^ğ•superscriptğ‘‘â€²\widehat{\mathbf{V}}_{d^{\prime}} and ğ•dâ€²subscriptğ•superscriptğ‘‘â€²\mathbf{V}_{d^{\prime}} [25, 30, 45, 42, 49]. To prove a utility guarantee, a common tool is the Davis-Kahan Theorem [8, 57], which assumes that the covariance matrix has a spectral gap [15, 25, 29, 35, 42]. Alternatively, using the projection error to evaluate accuracy is independent of the spectral gap [38, 44, 5]. In our implementation of private PCA, we donâ€™t treat ğ•^dâ€²subscript^ğ•superscriptğ‘‘â€²\widehat{\mathbf{V}}_{d^{\prime}} as our terminal output. Instead, we project ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X} onto ğ•^dâ€²subscript^ğ•superscriptğ‘‘â€²\widehat{\mathbf{V}}_{d^{\prime}}. Our approach directly bound the Wasserstein distance between the projected dataset and ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X}. This method circumvents the subspace perturbation analysis, resulting in an accuracy bound independent of the spectral gap, as outlined in Lemma 3.2. [49] considered a related task that takes a true dataset close to a low-dimensional linear subspace and outputs a private linear subspace. To the best of our knowledge, none of the previous work on private PCA considered low-dimensional DP synthetic data generation.

Centered covariance matrix

A common choice of the covariance matrix for PCA is 1nâ€‹ğ—ğ—ğ–³1ğ‘›superscriptğ—ğ—ğ–³\frac{1}{n}\mathbf{X}\mathbf{X}^{\mathsf{T}} [14, 25, 49], which is different from the centered one defined in (1.2). The rank of ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X} is the dimension of the linear subspace that the data lie in rather than that of the affine subspace. If ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X} lies in a dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional affine space (not necessarily passing through the origin), centering the data shifts the affine hyperplane spanned ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X} to pass through the origin. Consequently, the centered covariance matrix will have rank dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}, whereas the rank of ğ—ğ—\mathbf{X} is dâ€²+1superscriptğ‘‘â€²1d^{\prime}+1. By reducing the dimension of the linear subspace by 111, the centering step enhances the accuracy rate from (Îµâ€‹n)âˆ’1/(dâ€²+1)superscriptğœ€ğ‘›1superscriptğ‘‘â€²1(\varepsilon n)^{-1/(d^{\prime}+1)} to (Îµâ€‹n)âˆ’1/dâ€²superscriptğœ€ğ‘›1superscriptğ‘‘â€²(\varepsilon n)^{-1/d^{\prime}} . Yet, this process introduces the challenge of protecting the privacy of mean vectors, as detailed in the third step in AlgorithmÂ 1 and AlgorithmÂ 3.

Private covariance estimation

Private covariance estimation [18, 45] is closely linked to the private covariance matrix and the private linear projection components of our AlgorithmÂ 1. Instead of adding i.i.d. noise, [38, 4] improved the dependence on dğ‘‘d in the estimation error by sampling top eigenvectors with the exponential mechanism. However, it requires dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime} as an input parameter (in our approach, it can be chosen privately) and a lower bound on Ïƒdâ€²â€‹(ğŒ)subscriptğœsuperscriptğ‘‘â€²ğŒ\sigma_{d^{\prime}}(\mathbf{M}). The dependence on dğ‘‘d is a critical aspect in private mean estimation [37, 43], and it is an open question to determine the optimal dependence on dğ‘‘d for low-dimensional synthetic data generation.

2. Preliminaries

2.1. Differential Privacy

We use the following definition of Îµğœ€\varepsilon-differential privacy from [24]. Definition 2.1 (Differential privacy).

A randomized algorithm â„³:Î©nâ†’â„›:â„³superscriptÎ©ğ‘›â†’â„›\mathcal{M}\mathrel{\mathop{\mathchar 58\relax}}\Omega^{n}\to\mathcal{R} provides Îµğœ€\varepsilon-differential privacy if for any input data D,Dâ€²ğ·superscriptğ·â€²D,D^{\prime} that differs on only one element (or Dğ·D and Dâ€²superscriptğ·â€²D^{\prime} are adjacent datasets) and for any measurable set SâŠ†rangeâ€‹(â„³)ğ‘†rangeâ„³S\subseteq\mathrm{range}(\mathcal{M}), there is

â„™â€‹{â„³â€‹(D)âˆˆS}â‰¤eÎµâ‹…â„™â€‹{â„³â€‹(Dâ€²)âˆˆS}.â„™â„³ğ·ğ‘†â‹…superscriptğ‘’ğœ€â„™â„³superscriptğ·â€²ğ‘†{\mathbb{P}\{\mathcal{M}(D)\in S\}}\leq e^{\varepsilon}\cdot{\mathbb{P}\{\mathcal{M}(D^{\prime})\in S\}}.

Here the probability is taken from the probability space of the randomness of â„³â„³\mathcal{M}.

7. Conclusion

In this paper, we provide a DP algorithm to generate synthetic data, which closely approximates the true data in the hypercube [0,1]dsuperscript01ğ‘‘[0,1]^{d} under 1-Wasserstein distance. Moreover, when the true data lies in a dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional affine subspace, we improve the accuracy guarantees in [31] and circumvents the curse of dimensionality by generating a synthetic dataset close to the affine subspace.

It remains open to determine the optimal dependence on dğ‘‘d in the accuracy bound in Theorem 5.2 and whether the third term in (5.1) is needed. Our analysis of private PCA works without using the classical Davis-Kahan inequality that requires a spectral gap on the dataset. However, to approximate a dataset close to a line (dâ€²=1superscriptğ‘‘â€²1d^{\prime}=1), additional assumptions are needed in our analysis to achieve the near-optimal accuracy rate, see SectionÂ 6. It is an interesting problem to achieve an optimal rate without the dependence on Ïƒ1â€‹(ğŒ)subscriptğœ1ğŒ\sigma_{1}(\mathbf{M}) when dâ€²=1superscriptğ‘‘â€²1d^{\prime}=1.

Our Algorithm 1 only outputs synthetic data with a low-dimensional linear structure, and its analysis heavily relies on linear algebra tools. For original datasets from a dâ€²superscriptğ‘‘â€²d^{\prime}-dimensional linear subspace, we improve the accuracy rate from (Îµâ€‹n)âˆ’1/(dâ€²+1)superscriptğœ€ğ‘›1superscriptğ‘‘â€²1(\varepsilon n)^{-1/(d^{\prime}+1)} in [19] to (Îµâ€‹n)âˆ’1/dâ€²superscriptğœ€ğ‘›1superscriptğ‘‘â€²(\varepsilon n)^{-1/d^{\prime}}. It is also interesting to provide algorithms with optimal accuracy rates for datasets from general low-dimensional manifolds beyond the linear setting.
